§ 13. bonorum: masculine. aliud . . . tendebat: an example of the common development in language by which an originally intransitive verb becomes transitive. In this word the construction is first found in poetry.

§ 14. excretam: a Vergilian word. urbanae: previously not specially distinguished from the rusticae tribus. Henceforward they were of less importance than the others, their large numbers for one thing making the individual vote in them less weighty than that in the country tribeS. So an Irish vote is worth more than a vote in many English constituencieS.

§ 15. acceptam (sc. esse): not the adjective here, but the verb, so that animis is not dative. transveherentur: the trans- vectio equitum was from the temple of Honos before the porta Capena through the sorum to the Capitol.
